00:00:14.470 --> 00:00:16.800
VIVIAN CROMWELL: Welcome to the
second episode of Women

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:18.190
Techmakers.

00:00:18.190 --> 00:00:21.410
So we first started Women
Techmakers around Google I/O

00:00:21.410 --> 00:00:22.340
back in May.

00:00:22.340 --> 00:00:25.540
It was so well-received, so
we decided to bring back a

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:29.620
week-long series of five amazing
and fabulous woman to

00:00:29.620 --> 00:00:32.680
talk about their experience
in the tech industry.

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.730
So today we have a special
guest, Mary Lou Jepsen.

00:00:36.730 --> 00:00:40.550
Before we get started, let me
quickly introduce myself.

00:00:40.550 --> 00:00:44.460
So I head up our global Chrome
developer relations team.

00:00:44.460 --> 00:00:47.230
So our mission is to teach
web developers how to

00:00:47.230 --> 00:00:48.680
build great web apps.

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:51.170
So it has been great experience
working on the most

00:00:51.170 --> 00:00:53.900
amazing products with the
most amazing people.

00:00:53.900 --> 00:00:55.450
So I'm joined by Jean.

00:00:55.450 --> 00:00:56.270
JEAN WANG: Hi, everybody.

00:00:56.270 --> 00:00:57.770
My name is Jean Wang.

00:00:57.770 --> 00:01:01.510
I'm a lead hardware engineer
at Google X Project Class.

00:01:01.510 --> 00:01:04.680
And excuse me today for not
wearing my Glass device, it's

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:06.250
currently charging.

00:01:06.250 --> 00:01:09.620
And I'm really excited to have
Mary Lou with us here today.

00:01:09.620 --> 00:01:12.170
She has spearheaded a number
of display technologies,

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:15.000
including microdisplay, which
is actually near and dear to

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.450
our hearts at Google
X as well.

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:18.980
Mary Lou, would you like
to introduce yourself?

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:19.040
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Sure.

00:01:19.040 --> 00:01:20.240
I'm Mary Lou Jepsen.

00:01:20.240 --> 00:01:21.640
And I just want to
correct, I think

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:23.100
there's 15 amazing women.

00:01:23.100 --> 00:01:27.310
So you guys, all the amazing
hardware people at Google and

00:01:27.310 --> 00:01:29.650
software and technology
people at Google.

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:31.270
So thank you for inviting me.

00:01:31.270 --> 00:01:33.330
I'm big fans of yours.

00:01:33.330 --> 00:01:35.790
My background, I'm the founder
and CEO of a company called

00:01:35.790 --> 00:01:40.160
Pixel Qi, which is a spin-out
of a previous organization I

00:01:40.160 --> 00:01:42.640
co-founded with Nicholas
Negroponte called One Laptop

00:01:42.640 --> 00:01:45.330
per Child where I architected
the $100 laptop.

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:48.760
And it turns out that there was
a lot of great technology

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:50.020
in that laptop.

00:01:50.020 --> 00:01:53.880
It wasn't just a cheap laptop,
so much so that the CEOs of

00:01:53.880 --> 00:01:58.420
some of the big device makers of
the world really wanted the

00:01:58.420 --> 00:02:01.450
low power management and screen
architectures that I

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:05.710
had developed for this thing,
the $100 laptop.

00:02:05.710 --> 00:02:08.930
And so I spun out and I created
a for-profit company

00:02:08.930 --> 00:02:12.190
called Pixel Qi where we've now
shipped about 3 million

00:02:12.190 --> 00:02:16.310
different units across using the
excess fab capacity of the

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:19.470
world's LCD fabs to create
really innovative screen

00:02:19.470 --> 00:02:21.990
architecture that's
really low power.

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:25.570
Before that, I founded a
microdisplay company and I was

00:02:25.570 --> 00:02:28.750
a professor at MIT for a
while, and so forth.

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:30.870
JEAN WANG: Can you talk a bit
more about that evolution and

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:33.900
trajectory in your professional
life and how it's

00:02:33.900 --> 00:02:36.370
gotten to where you are
today with Pixel Qi?

00:02:36.370 --> 00:02:38.050
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Ah, sure.

00:02:38.050 --> 00:02:42.630
I really liked art and
I really liked math.

00:02:42.630 --> 00:02:47.570
And it turned out that met with
some push from my parents

00:02:47.570 --> 00:02:51.440
to be an electrical engineering
major because they

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:54.700
wanted me to be able to get
a job when I graduated.

00:02:54.700 --> 00:02:56.970
The deal was they would help
me pay for college

00:02:56.970 --> 00:02:58.550
if I got an EE degree.

00:02:58.550 --> 00:03:02.080
But I found the first couple
of years of EE pretty

00:03:02.080 --> 00:03:05.620
stifling, like if I had
any creativity it

00:03:05.620 --> 00:03:06.670
would've crushed it.

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:10.160
So to sort of maintain my
sanity, I kept my art going

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:13.110
and got pretty much
a degree in art as

00:03:13.110 --> 00:03:14.400
well at the same time.

00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:18.170
And that combined itself for
me, first, in holography.

00:03:18.170 --> 00:03:21.740
I started doing 3D things with
lasers and stuff, and

00:03:21.740 --> 00:03:24.240
holographic video, and just
different display

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:24.980
technologies.

00:03:24.980 --> 00:03:29.080
So I just really liked doing a
technically really hard puzzle

00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:31.920
and kind of the reward is this
beautiful image at the end.

00:03:31.920 --> 00:03:34.284
So that's what I do now.

00:03:34.284 --> 00:03:34.666
JEAN WANG: Great.

00:03:34.666 --> 00:03:37.690
Can you talk a bit about the
current state of the hardware

00:03:37.690 --> 00:03:39.980
industry in terms of
the display and

00:03:39.980 --> 00:03:40.720
where you see it going.

00:03:40.720 --> 00:03:44.690
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Yeah, it's
really interesting.

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:46.620
Trauma is a nice
way to put it.

00:03:46.620 --> 00:03:49.610
I mean right now there's not
a single profitable display

00:03:49.610 --> 00:03:51.610
manufacturer in the world.

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:53.660
They're running at negative
20% margin.

00:03:53.660 --> 00:03:55.350
They have been for a
number of years.

00:03:55.350 --> 00:03:57.490
I think Sharp just forecasted
they're going to lose $6

00:03:57.490 --> 00:04:03.460
billion, Panasonic worse,
nearly $10 billion.

00:04:03.460 --> 00:04:05.490
Negative 20% margin
for a number of

00:04:05.490 --> 00:04:07.740
years is hard to maintain.

00:04:07.740 --> 00:04:09.610
It's actually geopolitical.

00:04:09.610 --> 00:04:13.280
China's building up more
manufacturing capacity and

00:04:13.280 --> 00:04:14.770
there's just excess capacity.

00:04:14.770 --> 00:04:16.040
So there's that.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:18.810
And then in the device space,
Apple and Samsung have

00:04:18.810 --> 00:04:21.980
executed very, very well,
as I think, duh,

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:23.260
everybody knows that.

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:26.350
What maybe doesn't sort of
make the stage as sort of

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:32.790
pronounced is that everybody
else, HP, Dell, Nokia, RIM,

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:37.530
Asus, Acer are running at nearly
just about break-even.

00:04:37.530 --> 00:04:40.290
And a lot of R and D
has been slashed.

00:04:40.290 --> 00:04:45.490
And so, there is just very
few innovative--

00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:48.100
you're doing one of the most
innovative hardware programs

00:04:48.100 --> 00:04:49.340
on the planet yourself--

00:04:49.340 --> 00:04:53.870
but there's just very, very
little of that today.

00:04:53.870 --> 00:04:55.910
I think Andreessen says software
eats the world.

00:04:55.910 --> 00:04:58.400
That's great, but it still has
to run on something, and

00:04:58.400 --> 00:04:59.490
there's still this device.

00:04:59.490 --> 00:05:04.340
And if it's all Apple something,
god help us because

00:05:04.340 --> 00:05:06.780
they're going to control the
whole stream of data.

00:05:06.780 --> 00:05:09.340
We need, I think, more
diversity, and we're

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:10.010
searching for that.

00:05:10.010 --> 00:05:12.040
I like Apple products,
I like all of them.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:15.120
But I just think it's more
interesting if there was more

00:05:15.120 --> 00:05:17.300
than just two companies
shipping

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:20.890
devices in huge volumes.

00:05:20.890 --> 00:05:22.880
JEAN WANG: So how is Pixel Qi
and how are you doing your

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:25.370
part to try to make the display
industry profitable?

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:30.170
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Well, even when
I designed this thing,

00:05:30.170 --> 00:05:34.570
the reason I created a new
screen was cost, but it was

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:35.500
also power.

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:38.420
In the developing world,
kids don't have power

00:05:38.420 --> 00:05:39.240
outlets in the wall.

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:40.810
Or if they do, they're
not on all the time.

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:43.800
So this is a 1 watt laptop.

00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:46.600
The next laptop up is
about 10 watts.

00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:49.220
And that comes from a lot
of the power management

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:50.360
architecture that we created.

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:54.430
So what are we doing is
continuing that march down in

00:05:54.430 --> 00:05:58.270
a world where, since I made
this, the power consumption of

00:05:58.270 --> 00:06:01.930
screens has quadrupled in the
last three to four years.

00:06:01.930 --> 00:06:05.050
This is in a world where Intel
will respin a chip to save 10

00:06:05.050 --> 00:06:09.810
milliwatts, Qualcomm will fight
about microwatts, and

00:06:09.810 --> 00:06:13.290
the screen power consumption
has gone up like 5 watts.

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:16.460
If you look at like an iPad 3,
Apple's, sort of one of their

00:06:16.460 --> 00:06:20.270
flagship products, it's a 9 watt
machine, 8 watts of that

00:06:20.270 --> 00:06:21.780
is taken by the screen.

00:06:21.780 --> 00:06:26.130
So what we figured out how to do
is how to basically take 7

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:29.090
watts out of that, not 7
milliwatts, not 7 microwatts,

00:06:29.090 --> 00:06:32.820
7 watts, while maintaining the
front-of-screen performance,

00:06:32.820 --> 00:06:37.460
including the resolution and so
forth, viewing angle, color

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:39.850
saturation, contrast,
and all of that.

00:06:39.850 --> 00:06:42.020
So that's our next generation
architecture.

00:06:42.020 --> 00:06:44.470
But we've done that by building
up starting with this

00:06:44.470 --> 00:06:49.600
screen in here that's sunlight
readable and really working on

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:53.080
basically what I call small
aperture pixels.

00:06:53.080 --> 00:06:55.720
As you increase the screen
resolution, if the transistor

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:58.380
stays the same size, it
takes up more and more

00:06:58.380 --> 00:06:59.270
of the pixel area.

00:06:59.270 --> 00:07:02.210
That means the light from the
backlight gets blocked and

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:03.110
can't get through.

00:07:03.110 --> 00:07:05.320
And so you've got to crank up
that backlight and you've got

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:07.540
to power all those
extra pixels.

00:07:07.540 --> 00:07:11.230
Power is a huge deal.

00:07:11.230 --> 00:07:13.440
Maybe it's not even power,
it's thermal management.

00:07:13.440 --> 00:07:15.290
It's what do you do
with the heat.

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:18.810
You can use the best batteries
you want, but even still the

00:07:18.810 --> 00:07:20.690
iPad 3 is overheating.

00:07:20.690 --> 00:07:22.690
There's the thermal budget.

00:07:22.690 --> 00:07:25.450
And so if the pixels are
getting smaller and the

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:28.220
transistors stay the same size
and you crank it up, all that

00:07:28.220 --> 00:07:31.130
power goes to the screen
rather than a zippier

00:07:31.130 --> 00:07:34.850
processor, multitasking, being
able to beam video around,

00:07:34.850 --> 00:07:37.650
being able to beam video to the
Google Glass, whatever.

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:40.930
You can use power for a lot of
different things if the screen

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:41.740
isn't hogging it.

00:07:41.740 --> 00:07:44.120
So we're working on
that problem.

00:07:44.120 --> 00:07:47.160
And what we've done is over the
last eight years increased

00:07:47.160 --> 00:07:48.960
the front-of-screen
performance.

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:55.630
So now we can match that of
OLED, or any of the Android

00:07:55.630 --> 00:07:57.585
screens, or Motorola.

00:07:57.585 --> 00:08:02.690
I don't mean to just pick on
Apple, but at a competitive

00:08:02.690 --> 00:08:05.990
screen performance, including
the contrast, color, viewing

00:08:05.990 --> 00:08:08.340
angle, resolution,
and so forth.

00:08:08.340 --> 00:08:09.360
So that's what we've
been doing.

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:12.451
VIVIAN CROMWELL: Is One Laptop
per Child, the laptop, it's

00:08:12.451 --> 00:08:14.710
also [? convenient ?] to improve
the screen display?

00:08:14.710 --> 00:08:17.094
Because I know I read
recently they also

00:08:17.094 --> 00:08:18.900
started having tablets.

00:08:18.900 --> 00:08:20.380
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Yes, so
we're designing the

00:08:20.380 --> 00:08:21.600
screen for the tablet.

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:23.310
And we have improved
the front-of-screen

00:08:23.310 --> 00:08:24.980
performance of this.

00:08:24.980 --> 00:08:26.645
Oh, I just turned it off.

00:08:26.645 --> 00:08:28.680
I'll turn it back on.

00:08:28.680 --> 00:08:34.370
But you can see, and I brought
a big flashlight to show you.

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:37.570
But yeah, so One Laptop per
Child, I developed the screen

00:08:37.570 --> 00:08:39.530
for it and we continue
to support them.

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:44.750
When I created Pixel Qi, it was
a spin-off from a hardware

00:08:44.750 --> 00:08:46.730
charity, a nonprofit.

00:08:46.730 --> 00:08:49.480
And so we did a cross-licensing
deal where we

00:08:49.480 --> 00:08:52.520
get the IP and all the patent
stuff from One Laptop per

00:08:52.520 --> 00:08:56.230
Child to use, to continue to
develop, and we give them

00:08:56.230 --> 00:09:00.650
access to all of our IP that
we invent forever for their

00:09:00.650 --> 00:09:02.800
nonprofit humanitarian goals.

00:09:02.800 --> 00:09:08.810
So we still support them also
with finding vendors and

00:09:08.810 --> 00:09:10.290
things especially in Asia.

00:09:10.290 --> 00:09:13.460
I spend most of my
time in Asia.

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:13.770
JEAN WANG: It's really
impressive

00:09:13.770 --> 00:09:15.450
about the power savings.

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:18.560
Can you talk about that
discovery process and how you

00:09:18.560 --> 00:09:22.760
invent these new architectures
to achieve the savings?

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:24.286
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Ah, yeah,
how did it invent?

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:32.640
If you think of this, I've
got it back up and I

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:34.856
can show you that.

00:09:34.856 --> 00:09:38.360
Actually, I've got
a big flashlight.

00:09:38.360 --> 00:09:40.780
This is the brightest flashlight
on the planet that

00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:44.420
you can carry on a plane.

00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:47.440
And so you can see it's
sunlight readable.

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:50.620
And so it came from sort
of thinking about

00:09:50.620 --> 00:09:52.430
really wanting E Ink.

00:09:52.430 --> 00:09:56.130
And that's like compared to my
supposedly sunlight readable

00:09:56.130 --> 00:09:58.763
Nokia Lumia phone.

00:10:03.510 --> 00:10:09.240
This one, how do you invent in
general is you throw a lot of

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:13.910
ideas and see what sticks, I
think, and work through.

00:10:13.910 --> 00:10:16.190
And I just think about
it all the time.

00:10:16.190 --> 00:10:18.290
I can't sleep, I wake up.

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:20.750
In this case, the kids had to
get their laptops, how are you

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:21.480
going to solve it?

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:22.450
Oh my gosh.

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:25.830
It was like falling in love
almost, complete with not

00:10:25.830 --> 00:10:29.340
being able to sleep past 3:00
in the morning and waking up

00:10:29.340 --> 00:10:35.410
and thinking, how am I going
to do it, how do we do it?

00:10:35.410 --> 00:10:39.170
But the progression of this
screen to our next screens and

00:10:39.170 --> 00:10:42.880
our next screens came from sort
of a point of discovery.

00:10:42.880 --> 00:10:46.380
We figured out how to make a
really good small aperture

00:10:46.380 --> 00:10:48.720
screen because we wanted to
use most of the pixel to

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.450
reflect the light.

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:53.130
Like why fight the sun,
why not use it?

00:10:53.130 --> 00:10:55.730
So we developed an architecture
where we could

00:10:55.730 --> 00:10:59.870
hide a lot of circuitry
underneath those mirrors.

00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:02.340
We got rid of one layer in the
top substrate and added a

00:11:02.340 --> 00:11:04.290
layer to the bottom substrate.

00:11:04.290 --> 00:11:09.030
And it wasn't obvious to me that
that could make a large

00:11:09.030 --> 00:11:12.780
difference in where other screen
technology was going.

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:19.560
But we've actually created a
lot of different IP around

00:11:19.560 --> 00:11:22.840
that idea to solve a lot of our
customers' problems and a

00:11:22.840 --> 00:11:24.730
lot of the problems that
we want to solve as

00:11:24.730 --> 00:11:26.770
we invent new screens.

00:11:26.770 --> 00:11:28.980
I guess I'm not really answering
the question though.

00:11:28.980 --> 00:11:30.660
Like how do you invent?

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:31.480
I don't know.

00:11:31.480 --> 00:11:34.040
I just like noodling
on problems.

00:11:34.040 --> 00:11:36.100
JEAN WANG: I think some of it's,
of course, you do it off

00:11:36.100 --> 00:11:38.410
on your own when you're
sleeping, perhaps dreaming

00:11:38.410 --> 00:11:41.170
about it, or just having
lunch by yourself.

00:11:41.170 --> 00:11:44.010
And oftentimes, you just have
brainstorms with people that

00:11:44.010 --> 00:11:46.230
you work with and from
diverse perspectives.

00:11:46.230 --> 00:11:49.695
So optics team, plus the product
design team, plus the

00:11:49.695 --> 00:11:52.005
EE team getting together in one
room with manufacturing

00:11:52.005 --> 00:11:54.830
and just figuring out what are
the key issues that we have

00:11:54.830 --> 00:11:57.360
currently and what can we
do to attack it from a

00:11:57.360 --> 00:11:59.932
perspective we never
thought of before.

00:11:59.932 --> 00:12:01.670
So there is some of that.

00:12:01.670 --> 00:12:03.490
MARY LOU JEPSEN: I also like
the hard criticism.

00:12:03.490 --> 00:12:08.550
I find out more about that when
people tell me the things

00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:11.360
they don't like about what I
did, how come you didn't,

00:12:11.360 --> 00:12:13.540
especially if it's
something new.

00:12:13.540 --> 00:12:17.370
And sometimes they will tell
you that to your face.

00:12:17.370 --> 00:12:19.350
You know, Vinod Khosla has said
his Twitter stream is

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:21.180
very valuable for finding
out what people

00:12:21.180 --> 00:12:22.410
really think about him.

00:12:22.410 --> 00:12:25.400
They'll post it in blogs and
different things sometimes.

00:12:25.400 --> 00:12:29.190
Because it's just grown so
much, every little nit,

00:12:29.190 --> 00:12:32.760
people, you have fanboys too
even for Pixel Qi, and they

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:35.120
say what they like and what
