00:19:01.940 --> 00:19:03.700
whatever, tattoo it
on our bodies.

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:04.982
VIVIAN CROMWELL: A watch.

00:19:04.982 --> 00:19:06.010
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Certainly
the health care

00:19:06.010 --> 00:19:08.140
devices that will come.

00:19:08.140 --> 00:19:13.570
There's some merger of
mind and device.

00:19:13.570 --> 00:19:16.660
You're right there on
the head, I'm sure.

00:19:16.660 --> 00:19:17.900
You probably can't
talk about it.

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:20.410
JEAN WANG: Yeah, power is a
definite concern for Glass.

00:19:20.410 --> 00:19:22.650
And to be able to use the device
all day is something

00:19:22.650 --> 00:19:25.360
that we think seriously about.

00:19:25.360 --> 00:19:27.980
And so anything we could to do
to reduce the power from the

00:19:27.980 --> 00:19:31.880
display point of view, or even
the electronics, the audio

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:33.520
system that we have, all
of that is extremely

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:36.060
important to work on.

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:38.430
And we're always on the lookout,
not just as a big

00:19:38.430 --> 00:19:41.930
company, but looking at small
companies and innovations

00:19:41.930 --> 00:19:43.970
there for technology
improvement, for battery

00:19:43.970 --> 00:19:46.270
technology, and electronics.

00:19:46.270 --> 00:19:48.390
What is the [INAUDIBLE] thing
we can do to achieve a great

00:19:48.390 --> 00:19:49.680
user experience?

00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:50.290
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Right.

00:19:50.290 --> 00:19:52.520
And the battery technology
is getting better

00:19:52.520 --> 00:19:54.430
at about 10% a year.

00:19:54.430 --> 00:19:56.300
Maybe there's some breakthrough
stuff.

00:19:56.300 --> 00:19:58.700
There's some very interesting
companies.

00:19:58.700 --> 00:19:59.300
And that's good.

00:19:59.300 --> 00:20:03.030
But also there's the
charge time.

00:20:03.030 --> 00:20:06.950
And so if the device takes more
power because it's got a

00:20:06.950 --> 00:20:10.420
better innovative battery,
there's still the charge time

00:20:10.420 --> 00:20:13.300
to the battery.

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:16.430
And it's great because we can
use our mini USB adapters on

00:20:16.430 --> 00:20:19.355
most things, but that really
limits the charge time.

00:20:19.355 --> 00:20:20.300
It's only 5 volts.

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:25.100
And so it takes six,
seven hours to

00:20:25.100 --> 00:20:27.140
charge a typical tablet.

00:20:27.140 --> 00:20:30.780
In fact, the Motorola Xoom
tablet charges faster, which

00:20:30.780 --> 00:20:34.100
is why OLPC used it for a
deployment in Ethiopia,

00:20:34.100 --> 00:20:36.640
because it's got a 12 volt
special adapter so it can

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:37.890
charge twice as fast.

00:20:40.595 --> 00:20:44.270
Can we just make it so that
they can self power?

00:20:44.270 --> 00:20:47.130
If you're walking around, why
isn't that enough to charge it

00:20:47.130 --> 00:20:48.055
or a little bit of light?

00:20:48.055 --> 00:20:50.430
Can we get it down
to that low?

00:20:50.430 --> 00:20:52.430
And I think it's certainly
possible.

00:20:52.430 --> 00:20:55.390
It's very key in a lot of the
developing world where there

00:20:55.390 --> 00:20:59.020
isn't steady ready access
to electricity.

00:20:59.020 --> 00:21:00.850
You could say, well,
that will change.

00:21:00.850 --> 00:21:03.210
Infrastructure will be developed
if you wait 10

00:21:03.210 --> 00:21:06.040
years, 20 years.

00:21:06.040 --> 00:21:09.510
But some places it's hard to go
there and actually believe

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:13.710
that everybody will have ready
access to electricity.

00:21:13.710 --> 00:21:15.710
Because then you actually have
to think about the global

00:21:15.710 --> 00:21:22.650
warming issues and sort of how
much of our electronics are

00:21:22.650 --> 00:21:25.060
now the footprint of
our energy usage.

00:21:25.060 --> 00:21:27.880
In homes it used to be it was
the refrigerator that was the

00:21:27.880 --> 00:21:30.950
most power hungry thing,
now it's the TV.

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:36.720
And it's 10% of the power use
in a home is electronics.

00:21:36.720 --> 00:21:38.490
And as we get more electronics,
that goes up.

00:21:38.490 --> 00:21:41.040
So there's this whole green
level to it, which people

00:21:41.040 --> 00:21:43.690
don't think of in the first
level because you're focused

00:21:43.690 --> 00:21:47.350
on transportation being
one of the key things.

00:21:47.350 --> 00:21:50.430
But it's also just more
convenient if you don't have

00:21:50.430 --> 00:21:52.640
to power this stuff up.

00:21:52.640 --> 00:21:55.250
So consumers can vote.

00:21:55.250 --> 00:22:01.020
But there's certainly places
where we're not really able to

00:22:01.020 --> 00:22:03.170
compete with Apple or Samsung.

00:22:03.170 --> 00:22:05.520
If they only spent 10 times
what we did, we could.

00:22:05.520 --> 00:22:07.640
But they spend 1,000
times what we do.

00:22:07.640 --> 00:22:10.100
They spend billions and
we spend millions.

00:22:10.100 --> 00:22:13.590
So we actually have a nice
niche in our company.

00:22:13.590 --> 00:22:18.580
We serve 130 million people that
can't buy normal products

00:22:18.580 --> 00:22:21.020
from Apple, Samsung,
or other vendors

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:23.850
because they work outside.

00:22:23.850 --> 00:22:28.150
Construction workers, military,
cops, meter maids,

00:22:28.150 --> 00:22:30.290
truck drivers, they
all need stuff.

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:33.430
So we have stuff like this.

00:22:33.430 --> 00:22:34.200
It's kind of a brick.

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:38.130
But you can throw it on the
ground and it works or

00:22:38.130 --> 00:22:41.530
whatever, spill on it.

00:22:41.530 --> 00:22:44.870
And it's fine.

00:22:44.870 --> 00:22:48.050
But you can dunk and
different things.

00:22:48.050 --> 00:22:49.730
It says activate Windows now.

00:22:49.730 --> 00:22:51.320
And it's sunlight readable.

00:22:51.320 --> 00:22:54.410
I can even stand on it
if you want to see.

00:22:54.410 --> 00:22:57.720
VIVIAN CROMWELL: What is the
special usage of this device?

00:22:57.720 --> 00:23:00.440
Is it for the truck driver?

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:01.710
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Actually,
this is a new

00:23:01.710 --> 00:23:02.640
product from Trimble.

00:23:02.640 --> 00:23:04.780
And they actually have
the surveyors of the

00:23:04.780 --> 00:23:06.480
world, which are huge.

00:23:06.480 --> 00:23:08.810
They've got like 73%
of that market.

00:23:08.810 --> 00:23:12.590
So it's actually data input.

00:23:12.590 --> 00:23:15.300
There's even this in the back.

00:23:15.300 --> 00:23:17.940
But, yeah, I mean you can use it
for anything that you need

00:23:17.940 --> 00:23:18.480
to be outside.

00:23:18.480 --> 00:23:23.320
If it's getting mud on it, if
someone will roll over it, you

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:24.850
need the ruggedness.

00:23:24.850 --> 00:23:26.880
And you need to be able
to see it outside

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:28.880
for it to be useful.

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:31.580
The truth is, if we all
stayed inside all the

00:23:31.580 --> 00:23:32.490
time, it would be OK.

00:23:32.490 --> 00:23:34.970
But in reality, people
go outside.

00:23:34.970 --> 00:23:37.530
Most of us go outside
every day.

00:23:37.530 --> 00:23:39.400
We use our cell phones
outside.

00:23:39.400 --> 00:23:41.930
We use digital cameras
outside.

00:23:41.930 --> 00:23:44.510
You can't even tell if your
grandmother is smiling when

00:23:44.510 --> 00:23:46.710
you take a picture of her--
she may not be around that

00:23:46.710 --> 00:23:47.320
much longer--

00:23:47.320 --> 00:23:49.130
with all of today's devices
because you

00:23:49.130 --> 00:23:50.780
can't see them outside.

00:23:50.780 --> 00:23:53.670
So we're doing specialty
stuff for professional

00:23:53.670 --> 00:23:54.570
photographers.

00:23:54.570 --> 00:23:57.330
But we believe that people
will care about that, and

00:23:57.330 --> 00:23:58.960
power, and readability.

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:10.300
It's difficult in an
industry that is

00:24:10.300 --> 00:24:12.530
struggling like it is now.

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:17.010
So we persevere and we're pretty
happy about having this

00:24:17.010 --> 00:24:17.580
large niche.

00:24:17.580 --> 00:24:19.550
We go profitable
on this niche.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:23.930
But our big ambition is to
make innovative screens.

00:24:29.566 --> 00:24:32.860
In the year 2000 maybe, let's
call it 10 million laptops

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:34.420
shipped that year.

00:24:34.420 --> 00:24:35.890
There were tablets
that shipped.

00:24:35.890 --> 00:24:36.790
Apple didn't invent
the tablet.

00:24:36.790 --> 00:24:38.810
But it's much smaller numbers.

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:42.170
And so the volume that you
needed to achieve on a new

00:24:42.170 --> 00:24:44.760
product was relatively small.

00:24:44.760 --> 00:24:47.890
Fast forward to today where
you've got 250 million, 300

00:24:47.890 --> 00:24:50.375
million laptops, same amount
of desktops, 1

00:24:50.375 --> 00:24:51.980
billion cell phones.

00:24:51.980 --> 00:24:54.020
When you start mass production,
you have to be

00:24:54.020 --> 00:24:55.890
able to go to a million
units a month.

00:24:55.890 --> 00:24:57.810
That means you have to
use existing factory

00:24:57.810 --> 00:25:00.080
infrastructure or build your
own factory, which costs a

00:25:00.080 --> 00:25:01.320
couple billion dollars.

00:25:01.320 --> 00:25:04.140
If you spend a couple billion
dollars to build a factory,

00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:07.350
you've got to amortize that over
the output for, whatever,

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:09.430
five years.

00:25:09.430 --> 00:25:10.410
That's what Qualcomm did.

00:25:10.410 --> 00:25:14.470
They were basically wrapping a
$100 to $500 bill around every

00:25:14.470 --> 00:25:17.070
product they shipped as a
gift to the customer.

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:22.300
And so what we noticed is that
it's a moment, it seems to be,

00:25:22.300 --> 00:25:28.150
in the display industry where
it's a lot like 25 years ago

00:25:28.150 --> 00:25:30.310
in silicon where there were all
these different types of

00:25:30.310 --> 00:25:31.380
silicon processes.

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:34.060
There was CMOS, which
won, silicon on

00:25:34.060 --> 00:25:36.340
sapphire, gallium arsenide.

00:25:36.340 --> 00:25:39.400
And CMOS got good enough, it
wasn't the best, but it got

00:25:39.400 --> 00:25:43.480
good enough and the processes
reliable enough where more of

00:25:43.480 --> 00:25:44.540
those factories were made.

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:49.250
And people could basically
design a chip in software and

00:25:49.250 --> 00:25:51.150
send the file to the
manufacturer

00:25:51.150 --> 00:25:52.570
and back came a chip.

00:25:52.570 --> 00:25:55.100
So we think it's that moment
in the display industry.

00:25:55.100 --> 00:25:58.450
We're the only fabless LCD
company in the world.

00:25:58.450 --> 00:26:01.980
We're the only external team
that's ever gotten-- they

00:26:01.980 --> 00:26:05.460
still call it tape out, that's
how old the nomenclature is,

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:07.640
back when you had computer
tapes-- that has gotten to

00:26:07.640 --> 00:26:09.930
tape out into the big factories
of the world.

00:26:09.930 --> 00:26:13.600
Not even Apple gets that and
they get everything, for good

00:26:13.600 --> 00:26:14.520
reason mind you.

00:26:14.520 --> 00:26:19.670
But we've been doing that and
basically using as-is the

00:26:19.670 --> 00:26:23.560
factory process, Windows
processes, the materials that

00:26:23.560 --> 00:26:27.760
are allowed in the fab, and
re-architecting every single

00:26:27.760 --> 00:26:33.410
layer, the liquid crystal, how
we drive it, how we create

00:26:33.410 --> 00:26:34.030
structures.

00:26:34.030 --> 00:26:36.880
Because basically we're
playing with layers

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:38.110
of metal and oxide.

00:26:38.110 --> 00:26:39.950
Oxide, another word for
that's glass, right?

00:26:39.950 --> 00:26:44.250
And metal is a conductor and
oxide is an insulator, but

00:26:44.250 --> 00:26:45.390
metal is also a reflector.

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:48.050
And oxide is, well, glasses
are made out,

00:26:48.050 --> 00:26:49.080
there's lenses, right?

00:26:49.080 --> 00:26:52.710
And so you have to think of
shapes that can be both a

00:26:52.710 --> 00:26:58.550
transistor shape or a line shape
and have good electron

00:26:58.550 --> 00:27:03.370
mobility, while playing a double
role to bounce the

00:27:03.370 --> 00:27:05.990
light where you want the light
to go and in the way that you

00:27:05.990 --> 00:27:06.530
want it to go.

00:27:06.530 --> 00:27:08.090
And it's pretty fun.

00:27:08.090 --> 00:27:11.120
It's a very analog process.

00:27:11.120 --> 00:27:13.520
We work a lot on like
a small pixel, a 100

00:27:13.520 --> 00:27:14.570
micron square pixel.

00:27:14.570 --> 00:27:15.720
Then we make millions of them.

00:27:15.720 --> 00:27:18.080
We copy it when we
nail that pixel.

00:27:18.080 --> 00:27:24.180
And that's really what we are
trying to do in a world where

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:29.710
97% of all screens are liquid
crystal displays using thin

00:27:29.710 --> 00:27:31.320
film transistors.

00:27:31.320 --> 00:27:33.240
There are some other movements
in the industry.

00:27:33.240 --> 00:27:37.520
You're leading a fantastic one,
love LCOS or any of the

00:27:37.520 --> 00:27:39.110
microdisplay technologies.

00:27:39.110 --> 00:27:42.720
That's single crystal silicon
and you can do so much more in

00:27:42.720 --> 00:27:43.330
the backplane.

00:27:43.330 --> 00:27:46.730
And that's actually where
we came from.

00:27:46.730 --> 00:27:50.240
A lot of the people in the
company I have now I started

00:27:50.240 --> 00:27:54.145
working with in the mid '90s
when we started microdisplays.

00:27:54.145 --> 00:27:56.210
And there was a big microdisplay
effort.

00:27:56.210 --> 00:27:57.360
It was thought that
that was going to

00:27:57.360 --> 00:28:01.510
beat direct-view HDTV.

00:28:01.510 --> 00:28:03.660
We lost, LCD won.

00:28:03.660 --> 00:28:06.780
But we were developing
incredible innovation in the

00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:08.860
backplane because we had single
crystal silicon, we

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:13.800
could tape it out to those CMOS
fabs, back would come the

00:28:13.800 --> 00:28:17.200
