sort of can sit down and tell
you three levels down kind of

00:39:01.970 --> 00:39:03.380
a map for it.

00:39:05.970 --> 00:39:08.510
When I first started living in
Asia, I must have offended so

00:39:08.510 --> 00:39:08.910
many people.

00:39:08.910 --> 00:39:10.220
I was walking into walls.

00:39:10.220 --> 00:39:11.950
I didn't even know
they were walls.

00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:15.220
I didn't know that I was making
people angry with me.

00:39:15.220 --> 00:39:16.220
I didn't know that.

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:21.530
And I tried to get
forgiveness.

00:39:21.530 --> 00:39:25.430
VIVIAN CROMWELL: So Mary Lou,
when you grew up, what are

00:39:25.430 --> 00:39:28.540
some of the women role
models for you?

00:39:28.540 --> 00:39:31.000
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Well, my mom
who really encouraged me.

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:33.900
And I think actually
a VP at Google.

00:39:33.900 --> 00:39:38.460
I met her when I started at
MIT for grad school, Megan

00:39:38.460 --> 00:39:40.740
Smith became my best friend.

00:39:40.740 --> 00:39:44.190
And Margaret Minksy, Marvin
Minsky's daughter and Megan

00:39:44.190 --> 00:39:45.380
Smith shared an office.

00:39:45.380 --> 00:39:52.410
And Megan was just this
force of nature.

00:39:52.410 --> 00:39:56.890
That first year they made a
video of her for the Lego Logo

00:39:56.890 --> 00:39:59.600
people that became Mindstorms
called Megan in Motion.

00:39:59.600 --> 00:40:02.370
And she was just so high
energy, and just doing

00:40:02.370 --> 00:40:04.460
everything, and let's do it.

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:04.780
When?

00:40:04.780 --> 00:40:05.590
How about now?

00:40:05.590 --> 00:40:09.380
And so we'd sleep every other
day at that time.

00:40:09.380 --> 00:40:11.700
It just opened my eyes.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.545
I never really thought
about traveling.

00:40:16.170 --> 00:40:18.230
I just really liked
holography.

00:40:18.230 --> 00:40:20.590
So I was sort of niche,
I guess, then.

00:40:20.590 --> 00:40:23.780
And she kind of blew the
doors off of that.

00:40:27.600 --> 00:40:30.030
When I focused on holography,
what was really interesting is

00:40:30.030 --> 00:40:32.520
it was about half men
and half women in

00:40:32.520 --> 00:40:36.340
holography at that time.

00:40:36.340 --> 00:40:39.000
A lot of the women tended to be
artists, a lot of the men

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:43.570
tended to be techy, but there
was cross between both.

00:40:43.570 --> 00:40:47.510
And a woman, Paula Dawson, who's
a holographic artist in

00:40:47.510 --> 00:40:49.250
Australia, I went
and collaborated

00:40:49.250 --> 00:40:51.320
with her for a while.

00:40:51.320 --> 00:40:56.090
And I used to teach history
of science.

00:40:56.090 --> 00:41:00.470
And there's all these amazing
women if you look back that

00:41:00.470 --> 00:41:04.190
aren't fully recognized, but
really did amazing things.

00:41:04.190 --> 00:41:09.440
And one that I really like is
Lucia Galvani, who was the

00:41:09.440 --> 00:41:14.710
wife of Lucio Galvani, who
discovered basically a new

00:41:14.710 --> 00:41:17.790
kind of electricity
in about 1790.

00:41:17.790 --> 00:41:19.670
She actually observed.

00:41:19.670 --> 00:41:22.220
He was dissecting frogs and they
were outside and there

00:41:22.220 --> 00:41:24.150
was electrical sparks.

00:41:24.150 --> 00:41:26.720
It was either a generator, they
thought there were these

00:41:26.720 --> 00:41:28.373
different types of electricity
then, there

00:41:28.373 --> 00:41:29.510
were like five different.

00:41:29.510 --> 00:41:32.980
Ben Franklin discovered
one, the key.

00:41:32.980 --> 00:41:35.940
But anyway, the frog's
legs moved.

00:41:35.940 --> 00:41:41.600
And that meant electricity was
causing our muscles to move

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:42.220
inside of us.

00:41:42.220 --> 00:41:44.360
It inspired "Frankenstein,"
Mary Shelley that wrote

00:41:44.360 --> 00:41:47.570
"Frankenstein." But she made the
observation according to

00:41:47.570 --> 00:41:50.120
the history and doesn't
really get credit.

00:41:50.120 --> 00:41:54.020
Galvanism, galvanic, all of that
comes from the Galvanis.

00:41:54.020 --> 00:41:56.890
And I think there's tons of
women through history that

00:41:56.890 --> 00:42:03.650
just never got the credit
for what they did.

00:42:03.650 --> 00:42:06.610
VIVIAN CROMWELL: So you believe
women should really

00:42:06.610 --> 00:42:10.970
fight for the credit for the
work they're doing to be able

00:42:10.970 --> 00:42:15.210
to gain the recognition
in the office?

00:42:15.210 --> 00:42:16.700
MARY LOU JEPSEN: It's
interesting because the way

00:42:16.700 --> 00:42:19.110
you do that in Asia versus
here is different.

00:42:19.110 --> 00:42:28.420
But I think it's very critical
to find a way to get credit

00:42:28.420 --> 00:42:29.130
for the work.

00:42:29.130 --> 00:42:31.550
And the way I do that, I don't
know, you can talk to how you

00:42:31.550 --> 00:42:35.540
do it, I used to not do it.

00:42:35.540 --> 00:42:36.770
I didn't know how to do it.

00:42:36.770 --> 00:42:40.050
And then I realized, wow, I'm
just really excited when

00:42:40.050 --> 00:42:42.615
somebody gets something pretty
cool to work, and I tell

00:42:42.615 --> 00:42:44.240
everybody about how
cool it is.

00:42:44.240 --> 00:42:47.540
And then I just realized I
should also say, I got this

00:42:47.540 --> 00:42:48.940
work, isn't it great?

00:42:48.940 --> 00:42:49.570
I'm awesome.

00:42:49.570 --> 00:42:54.320
And then and tell the other
people like there's all these

00:42:54.320 --> 00:42:55.590
great things going on.

00:42:55.590 --> 00:43:01.030
And so I found it a lot easier
to take credit, also part of

00:43:01.030 --> 00:43:03.850
it is sort of becoming
a boss and learning

00:43:03.850 --> 00:43:05.750
how to do all that.

00:43:05.750 --> 00:43:08.920
But in my early years, I didn't
actually quite know how

00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:12.182
to do that.

00:43:12.182 --> 00:43:15.350
VIVIAN CROMWELL: Are there a
lot of female engineers in

00:43:15.350 --> 00:43:16.770
your organizations?

00:43:16.770 --> 00:43:19.010
Do you do anything trying
to encourage

00:43:19.010 --> 00:43:21.100
more females to enter?

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:21.960
MARY LOU JEPSEN: We do.

00:43:21.960 --> 00:43:24.060
We do have a lot of women
in our company.

00:43:24.060 --> 00:43:26.180
In fact, our VP of
manufacturing,

00:43:26.180 --> 00:43:27.540
Belle Fu, is amazing.

00:43:27.540 --> 00:43:29.500
She brought up four
different fabs in

00:43:29.500 --> 00:43:31.540
three different companies.

00:43:31.540 --> 00:43:33.780
She was a chemist by training
and then she went and got a

00:43:33.780 --> 00:43:38.760
Ph.D. in psychology because
the decisions taken didn't

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:41.920
actually make any
technical sense.

00:43:41.920 --> 00:43:44.210
So she runs all of our
fab relations.

00:43:44.210 --> 00:43:47.900
And it's really great because
we have to understand the

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:52.940
space the decision makers and
decision influences are in,

00:43:52.940 --> 00:43:55.080
because we are not their
top priority.

00:43:55.080 --> 00:43:58.110
We're just always at that sort
of are we in the fab or out of

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:01.340
fab because we're so
small and whatnot.

00:44:01.340 --> 00:44:03.950
So that's really key.

00:44:03.950 --> 00:44:07.360
And we have other
women as well.

00:44:10.490 --> 00:44:14.080
And would like more,
certainly.

00:44:14.080 --> 00:44:19.320
The numbers are pretty daunting,
I think, across the

00:44:19.320 --> 00:44:21.210
technical industries.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:22.570
It's depressing.

00:44:22.570 --> 00:44:26.120
JEAN WANG: So what sort of
advice would you give to be

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:30.050
able to rise into leadership
roles and to excel in their

00:44:30.050 --> 00:44:31.300
careers and development?

00:44:34.400 --> 00:44:36.930
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Advice,
it depends.

00:44:36.930 --> 00:44:42.180
I think, in one sentence,
is do the hard stuff.

00:44:42.180 --> 00:44:46.830
Do the hard stuff, learn
it, even if it's hard.

00:44:46.830 --> 00:44:50.020
And also stay passionate about
something, see if you can

00:44:50.020 --> 00:44:53.480
combine them, like whatever
the field is.

00:44:53.480 --> 00:44:58.050
Because if you don't understand
deeply how some of

00:44:58.050 --> 00:45:01.330
this stuff works, like
especially the stuff that

00:45:01.330 --> 00:45:03.810
maybe you don't like.

00:45:03.810 --> 00:45:06.830
Like I didn't like
some aspects.

00:45:06.830 --> 00:45:08.930
I hated inclined planes.

00:45:08.930 --> 00:45:09.920
I just hated it.

00:45:09.920 --> 00:45:11.480
I thought it was just a dumb.

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:14.700
I grew up on a farm, I never saw
once something go down at

00:45:14.700 --> 00:45:16.350
that force on an inclined
plane, it

00:45:16.350 --> 00:45:17.510
doesn't actually happen.

00:45:17.510 --> 00:45:20.310
I just thought the whole thing
was dumb and I had to do that

00:45:20.310 --> 00:45:22.610
for like a year for engineering
school.

00:45:22.610 --> 00:45:26.840
But it just seemed like I had to
stick through it to get to

00:45:26.840 --> 00:45:28.230
the other side.

00:45:28.230 --> 00:45:30.250
It's really just Newton's Law
and you've got to learn that.

00:45:30.250 --> 00:45:34.600
But different people have
barriers at different times.

00:45:34.600 --> 00:45:39.670
And I think, basically, if you
can do that, I've mastered a

00:45:39.670 --> 00:45:42.610
lot of different fields because
I loved holography and

00:45:42.610 --> 00:45:45.230
you couldn't actually get
a degree in holography.

00:45:45.230 --> 00:45:50.670
So I had to learn vision
science, and chemistry, and

00:45:50.670 --> 00:45:56.960
physics, and math, and art,
mechanics, and a lot of

00:45:56.960 --> 00:46:01.000
different things in order to
learn, how to program, and a

00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:03.090
lot of different things so that
I could make really good

00:46:03.090 --> 00:46:05.090
whole holograms.

00:46:05.090 --> 00:46:08.400
And then you realize that it's
OK, you can sort of catch up

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:09.540
quick in a field.

00:46:09.540 --> 00:46:13.020
And part of that is you have to
deal with, as a girl, like

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:14.340
they're all boys.

00:46:14.340 --> 00:46:21.670
And there's this thing, like
at MIT, people call people

00:46:21.670 --> 00:46:23.370
that don't know everything
like brain-dead.

00:46:23.370 --> 00:46:26.640
And I remember joining the
holography group at MIT.

00:46:26.640 --> 00:46:28.350
There was actually a
holography group.

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:30.130
And everybody kept talking
in these sort

00:46:30.130 --> 00:46:31.870
of weird coded terms.

00:46:31.870 --> 00:46:34.400
And there was a hologram that
was made and was called

00:46:34.400 --> 00:46:36.320
[? sanjigen. ?]

00:46:36.320 --> 00:46:37.860
And I didn't know what
[? sanjigen ?]

00:46:37.860 --> 00:46:41.450
meant in Japanese because
it was a Japanese word.

00:46:41.450 --> 00:46:43.090
It means 3D.

00:46:43.090 --> 00:46:45.790
And it just happened to be the
name of something and somehow

00:46:45.790 --> 00:46:47.570
I was supposed to know
what that meant.

00:46:47.570 --> 00:46:51.410
And there were so many levels
in figuring out what the

00:46:51.410 --> 00:46:54.440
context words, where if you
could just get through that,

00:46:54.440 --> 00:46:55.920
it's like hazing.

00:46:55.920 --> 00:46:58.930
It just feels like they don't
really write it down and you

00:46:58.930 --> 00:47:01.150
just have to figure out
a way through that.

00:47:01.150 --> 00:47:06.180
And some people will help you
eventually, as long as you

00:47:06.180 --> 00:47:07.600
sort of help them, I guess.

00:47:07.600 --> 00:47:10.710
And I think that part
is pretty hard.

00:47:10.710 --> 00:47:14.000
Because the assumption is that
when you're coming in,

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.780
especially as a younger woman,
or maybe it wasn't the

00:47:17.780 --> 00:47:19.700
assumption, maybe I just
felt it was that.

00:47:19.700 --> 00:47:22.640
The impostor syndrome thing is
that you must be an idiot

00:47:22.640 --> 00:47:24.360
because you don't know
this stuff already.

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:27.190
Like how on Earth was I supposed
to know the type of

00:47:27.190 --> 00:47:29.370
hologram that was called
[? sanjigen ?]

00:47:29.370 --> 00:47:32.270
was like this type of hologram
made this way.

00:47:32.270 --> 00:47:34.440
It's like impossible, right?

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:38.220
Do you guys have
maybe similar?

00:47:38.220 --> 00:47:41.860
JEAN WANG: Yeah, so I guess I've
been pretty lucky in a

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:44.200
way, despite going to an
engineering school.

00:47:44.200 --> 00:47:47.650
At Caltech the ratio is 3:1 for
engineering and even worse

00:47:47.650 --> 00:47:50.280
for EE, which was what
my degree was in.

00:47:50.280 --> 00:47:53.460
But after a while, at least
for me personally, I just

00:47:53.460 --> 00:47:54.220
didn't even notice.

00:47:54.220 --> 00:47:58.830
We were all just people trying
to get our degree, trying to

00:47:58.830 --> 00:48:01.390
get our A's or whatnot,
and doing research.

00:48:01.390 --> 00:48:04.776
And you don't really notice it
until somebody actually points

00:48:04.776 --> 00:48:06.420
it out to you.

00:48:06.420 --> 00:48:06.875
MARY LOU JEPSEN: That's
interesting.

00:48:06.875 --> 00:48:08.480
JEAN WANG: I think that's
been an evolution.

00:48:08.480 --> 00:48:10.200
And of course, we're standing
on the shoulders of all the

00:48:10.200 --> 00:48:12.580
women who have gone before us.

00:48:12.580 --> 00:48:14.520
And it will continue
to improve.

00:48:14.520 --> 00:48:19.950
But I think it's turning out to
be less of an issue now as

00:48:19.950 --> 00:48:20.960
it was in the past.

00:48:20.960 --> 00:48:24.100
And I hope it continues
to improve.

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:25.830
MARY LOU JEPSEN: I only noticed
that I was a woman

00:48:25.830 --> 00:48:26.900
when I was in the
younger years.

00:48:26.900 --> 00:48:29.920
But I used to lifeguard at the
beach in summers before I got

00:48:29.920 --> 00:48:32.105
my engineering jobs
in the summers.

00:48:32.105 --> 00:48:34.560
And I remember they'd all tell
me like they would never work

00:48:34.560 --> 00:48:37.250
for a woman, all the lifeguards
who were my

00:48:37.250 --> 00:48:39.960
colleagues on the beach.

00:48:39.960 --> 00:48:42.610
And that was sort of what
they would say then.

00:48:48.400 --> 00:48:51.280
I just stopped noticing.

00:48:51.280 --> 00:48:54.590
And I'm me, and it's their
problem, and it's [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:54.590 --> 00:48:57.140
more difficult.

00:48:57.140 --> 00:49:00.950
But then, that said, Middle
East is a different story.

00:49:00.950 --> 00:49:03.590
VIVIAN CROMWELL: I kind of
feel like I grew up in a

00:49:03.590 --> 00:49:07.200
pretty lucky environment because
my family is pretty

00:49:07.200 --> 00:49:09.950
heavily engineering oriented.

00:49:09.950 --> 00:49:12.710
My dad is a physics and
optical engineer.

00:49:12.710 --> 00:49:14.380
My mom is a mechanical
engineer.

00:49:14.380 --> 00:49:18.180
So as I grew up, I never really
realized there is a

00:49:18.180 --> 00:49:22.330
gender association to what
you can do and not.

00:49:22.330 --> 00:49:25.075
I think the first time I
actually realized that was

00:49:25.075 --> 00:49:28.070
probably after I graduated
from school.

00:49:28.070 --> 00:49:30.070
Because in all the companies
I applied for, they were

00:49:30.070 --> 00:49:33.232
actually putting a ratio of how
many males they want to

00:49:33.232 --> 00:49:34.400
hire, how many females.

00:49:34.400 --> 00:49:36.580
So that kind of struck me.

00:49:36.580 --> 00:49:39.890
Oh wow, they're actually
putting gender with the

00:49:39.890 --> 00:49:41.120
position you want to fill.

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:45.665
So in general, pretty lucky like
in terms of growing up in

00:49:45.665 --> 00:49:47.085
a very supportive environment.

00:49:50.200 --> 00:49:53.370
JEAN WANG: So now it's time for
our live question portion

00:49:53.370 --> 00:49:56.490
of the session.

00:49:56.490 --> 00:50:00.650
First question comes from
T.S. In California.

00:50:00.650 --> 00:50:04.650
She asks, or he asks, it's not
clear, with the future usage

00:50:04.650 --> 00:50:07.520
trend going into mobile
computing with smaller devices

00:50:07.520 --> 00:50:10.300
like tablet, should
OLPC become One

00:50:10.300 --> 00:50:12.670
Tablet per Child instead?

00:50:12.670 --> 00:50:15.530
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Well,
they're doing that.

00:50:15.530 --> 00:50:18.730
The laptops and the keyboards
are pretty useful.

00:50:18.730 --> 00:50:23.310
They've put touchscreen into
the latest version of this,

00:50:23.310 --> 00:50:25.180
which uses the same thing.

00:50:25.180 --> 00:50:28.270
And this thing actually
does turn around.

00:50:28.270 --> 00:50:30.980
It's big, it's bulky,
it's like a brick.

00:50:30.980 --> 00:50:31.580
Oh, sorry.

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:34.940
VIVIAN CROMWELL: Is this the
same, like $100 per tablet, or

00:50:34.940 --> 00:50:36.980
it's going to be a little
bit higher?

00:50:36.980 --> 00:50:39.200
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Probably
less, I think $75.

00:50:39.200 --> 00:50:42.710
They demoed it at CES last
year or year before.

00:50:42.710 --> 00:50:44.590
It got a lot of Best
of CES things.

00:50:44.590 --> 00:50:47.740
But the question is when it
goes into production.

00:50:47.740 --> 00:50:50.850
OLPC has done a very interesting
experiment of

00:50:50.850 --> 00:50:54.240
actually airdropping tablets.

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:57.240
And they use the Motorola Xooms
because they charge fast

00:50:57.240 --> 00:50:59.250
rather than starting a
pre-production run.

00:50:59.250 --> 00:51:00.780
They only have a small number.

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:05.280
They airdropped them into two
illiterate villages in Kenya

00:51:05.280 --> 00:51:08.280
about eight months ago to see
what would happen, places that

00:51:08.280 --> 00:51:11.470
there's no written languages,
nobody knows how to read.

00:51:11.470 --> 00:51:14.900
The adults, no language,
writing is used.

00:51:14.900 --> 00:51:19.650
And they wanted to see if the
kids would learn how to read

00:51:19.650 --> 00:51:20.990
or what would happen.

00:51:20.990 --> 00:51:22.790
In one village just the
kids used them.

00:51:22.790 --> 00:51:24.470
And in another village,
the kids and the

00:51:24.470 --> 00:51:26.385
adults used them together.

00:51:26.385 --> 00:51:30.540
But the kids have learned a lot
of pre-reading stuff, a

00:51:30.540 --> 00:51:32.080
lot of alphabet.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:35.510
The government decided primary
education in--

00:51:35.510 --> 00:51:35.890
Sorry, it's not.

00:51:35.890 --> 00:51:37.280
Kenya, it's Ethiopia--

00:51:37.280 --> 00:51:41.280
primary education in Ethiopia
is an Amharic, but secondary

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:43.090
and tertiary is in English.

00:51:43.090 --> 00:51:46.640
And so they thought, let's
put English on it.

00:51:46.640 --> 00:51:49.470
In fact, sidebar, we
made the first

00:51:49.470 --> 00:51:53.050
Amharic keyboard in OLPC.

00:51:53.050 --> 00:51:56.630
Nobody had ever made
one before.

00:51:56.630 --> 00:51:58.520
There was a lot of firsts
that we did.

00:51:58.520 --> 00:52:02.240
But tablets in the villages,
the kids started to

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:02.790
learn how to read.

00:52:02.790 --> 00:52:04.170
They also learned how
to hack them.

00:52:04.170 --> 00:52:08.370
Because OLPC had turned off the
camera features because

00:52:08.370 --> 00:52:12.170
they wore down the battery
really quickly.

00:52:12.170 --> 00:52:14.570
And the kids figured out how
to hack around and hack

00:52:14.570 --> 00:52:17.850
Android to turn on the camera.

00:52:17.850 --> 00:52:19.630
So that was great.

00:52:19.630 --> 00:52:25.130
But yeah, so tablets are very
important going forward.

00:52:25.130 --> 00:52:27.060
But different countries
are picking.

00:52:27.060 --> 00:52:29.450
Every child in Uruguay
has one of these.

00:52:29.450 --> 00:52:33.300
The Uruguayan government has
ordered another 100,000.

00:52:33.300 --> 00:52:36.600
About half the kids in Peru,
50 other countries, 26

00:52:36.600 --> 00:52:37.160
different languages.

00:52:37.160 --> 00:52:39.094
VIVIAN CROMWELL: So are those
mainly being distributed

00:52:39.094 --> 00:52:40.970
through the local government?

00:52:40.970 --> 00:52:42.830
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Through the
ministry of education, they

00:52:42.830 --> 00:52:45.505
buy them en masse like textbooks
and then give them

00:52:45.505 --> 00:52:49.870
out to the kids and they have
a lifetime of five years.

00:52:49.870 --> 00:52:52.985
And they could be with
tablets as well.

00:52:52.985 --> 00:52:57.420
VIVIAN CROMWELL: I'm wondering,
it seems that even

00:52:57.420 --> 00:53:00.180
outside the developing countries
there are a lot of

00:53:00.180 --> 00:53:03.134
other places kids can use
laptops like this, but I

00:53:03.134 --> 00:53:06.470
haven't really seen a lot of
massive adoption of these

00:53:06.470 --> 00:53:09.500
laptops outside the developing
countries.

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:11.030
I'm just kind of curious why.

00:53:11.030 --> 00:53:14.280
MARY LOU JEPSEN: I remember when
OLPC started, we had our

00:53:14.280 --> 00:53:16.210
first prototypes out.

00:53:16.210 --> 00:53:19.160
And the mayor of Birmingham,
Alabama walked into our office

00:53:19.160 --> 00:53:22.200
on day in Cambridge,
across from MIT.

00:53:22.200 --> 00:53:24.150
And he said, do what you
want, arrest me.

00:53:24.150 --> 00:53:25.300
He was a big guy.

00:53:25.300 --> 00:53:27.670
And he said, arrest me, do
what have to have to, I'm

00:53:27.670 --> 00:53:29.200
leaving here with two laptops.

00:53:29.200 --> 00:53:31.540
Call the cops, don't care.

00:53:31.540 --> 00:53:33.950
Because he wanted some for the
kids of Birmingham, Alabama.

00:53:33.950 --> 00:53:36.190
He got them, we gave him
some laptops, some

00:53:36.190 --> 00:53:37.200
of the other schools.

00:53:37.200 --> 00:53:40.280
But we really designed this one,
it's mesh networked so

00:53:40.280 --> 00:53:43.160
you don't need a Wi-Fi
connection, all the laptops

00:53:43.160 --> 00:53:44.690
talk to each other.

00:53:44.690 --> 00:53:47.460
We actually had to finish the
standard for 802.11s.

00:53:47.460 --> 00:53:50.350
S stands for mesh because
M was gone.

00:53:50.350 --> 00:53:56.520
But it's really a super low
power, sunlight readable,

00:53:56.520 --> 00:54:02.080
rugged laptop for kids that we
specifically designed for the

00:54:02.080 --> 00:54:02.830
developing world.

00:54:02.830 --> 00:54:06.290
Even there's like extra screws
underneath the keyboard in

00:54:06.290 --> 00:54:10.790
case the kids have to fix the
screws and they can fix,

00:54:10.790 --> 00:54:13.070
sorry, the laptop, and the
screws drop on the ground and

00:54:13.070 --> 00:54:15.020
they can't have it.

00:54:15.020 --> 00:54:16.390
There's a lot of solutions.

00:54:16.390 --> 00:54:19.440
I mean Chromebook might
be a good solution.

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:22.160
You guys are at $250
right now, right?

00:54:22.160 --> 00:54:23.810
That's pretty good.

00:54:23.810 --> 00:54:27.410
So there's a lot of different
solutions that exist now.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:31.320
When we started this thing eight
years ago, people really

00:54:31.320 --> 00:54:33.820
thought we were nuts.

00:54:33.820 --> 00:54:36.530
What Steve Jobs said, what Craig
Barrett said, what Bill

00:54:36.530 --> 00:54:39.750
Gates, I mean they
were shocking.

00:54:39.750 --> 00:54:42.740
They were insulting,
public and private

00:54:42.740 --> 00:54:43.960
derision from them.

00:54:43.960 --> 00:54:48.810
But what we did that was maybe
even more important--

00:54:48.810 --> 00:54:52.410
only 3 million are in the field,
that's not every kid--

00:54:52.410 --> 00:54:54.670
is change the agenda for
every minister of

00:54:54.670 --> 00:54:57.620
education on the planet.

00:54:57.620 --> 00:55:00.255
The job of the minister of
education is to educate the

00:55:00.255 --> 00:55:03.390
kids of their country, it's
the job of the country.

00:55:03.390 --> 00:55:06.610
And if you're living in a
developing world country, and

00:55:06.610 --> 00:55:09.750
I won't name the country, but a
large country in Africa, for

00:55:09.750 --> 00:55:13.310
example, a third of the teachers
that are paid to show

00:55:13.310 --> 00:55:16.770
up, don't show up, the next
third are literate.

00:55:16.770 --> 00:55:20.290
You're doing with one third of
the teachers that actually

00:55:20.290 --> 00:55:22.600
show up, try to do right
by the kids,

00:55:22.600 --> 00:55:24.580
and know how to read.

00:55:24.580 --> 00:55:26.260
At that point, better
teacher training

00:55:26.260 --> 00:55:27.310
doesn't solve the problem.

00:55:27.310 --> 00:55:29.020
You just realize the
kids are smart.

00:55:29.020 --> 00:55:32.520
When you want to fix, maybe
not a Google, but normal

00:55:32.520 --> 00:55:35.270
everyday people, when they want
to fix an electronics

00:55:35.270 --> 00:55:36.710
problem, they hand it
to a kid, right?

00:55:36.710 --> 00:55:40.150
Because kids, they're sponges,
they figure it out.

00:55:40.150 --> 00:55:44.460
By definition, one or two of us
in every 100 are geniuses.

00:55:44.460 --> 00:55:46.680
By definition, we
say that, right?

00:55:46.680 --> 00:55:47.800
They're going to
figure it out.

00:55:47.800 --> 00:55:50.900
And the situation is so bad in
so much of the developing

00:55:50.900 --> 00:55:53.040
world you have to leverage
the kids themselves.

00:55:53.040 --> 00:55:57.030
So sure, computers are also
being used in the classroom,

00:55:57.030 --> 00:56:01.900
Khan Academy, all this great
stuff that's happening

00:56:01.900 --> 00:56:02.850
everywhere.

00:56:02.850 --> 00:56:06.710
But we were focused
on the developing

00:56:06.710 --> 00:56:08.210
world for that program.

00:56:14.476 --> 00:56:16.886
VIVIAN CROMWELL: That's the only
question we have on the

00:56:16.886 --> 00:56:19.300
Google Moderator.

00:56:19.300 --> 00:56:21.320
JEAN WANG: Actually, I do have
a follow-up question to that,

00:56:21.320 --> 00:56:24.390
is how do you take the feedback
that you get on OLPC,

00:56:24.390 --> 00:56:28.170
for example, and how do you roll
that into the next design

00:56:28.170 --> 00:56:29.790
or improvements?

00:56:29.790 --> 00:56:32.960
MARY LOU JEPSEN: I think a lot
of the feedback that OLPC got,

00:56:32.960 --> 00:56:34.660
and I haven't been with
the organization

00:56:34.660 --> 00:56:36.040
now for four years.

00:56:36.040 --> 00:56:40.050
But a lot of the feedback
they got was on, what

00:56:40.050 --> 00:56:41.220
do the tests show?

00:56:41.220 --> 00:56:43.460
And there was a lot of testing,
particularly in

00:56:43.460 --> 00:56:46.420
Uruguay and Peru, where there
were very large deployments.

00:56:46.420 --> 00:56:51.130
Rwanda, Afghanistan, Pakistan
had bigger deployments as I

00:56:51.130 --> 00:56:52.160
understand it.

00:56:52.160 --> 00:56:57.560
And some of the feedback on the
testing was, sure, truancy

00:56:57.560 --> 00:57:01.070
went down, community engagement
went up, kids were

00:57:01.070 --> 00:57:03.870
online, but were their
test scores better?

00:57:03.870 --> 00:57:06.080
In some cases they were better,
in some cases they

00:57:06.080 --> 00:57:07.120
were about the same.

00:57:07.120 --> 00:57:16.800
But the truth is I think OLPC
has been criticized for not

00:57:16.800 --> 00:57:18.670
doing enough testing.

00:57:18.670 --> 00:57:25.080
That said, I think literacy
rates in Peru there's like

00:57:25.080 --> 00:57:27.195
these different levels
they measure.

00:57:27.195 --> 00:57:28.910
I can't remember the
numbers of them.

00:57:28.910 --> 00:57:32.410
But in villages, Peru went into
places that didn't have

00:57:32.410 --> 00:57:35.000
electricity, or internet,
or anything

00:57:35.000 --> 00:57:36.250
to deploy the laptops.

00:57:39.390 --> 00:57:42.730
Sorry, something's beeping, I
don't know which one, probably

00:57:42.730 --> 00:57:44.400
my cell phone.

00:57:44.400 --> 00:57:49.190
In those places, there was like
90% of the kids couldn't

00:57:49.190 --> 00:57:53.410
even pass to the sort of base
level, which, I think, there

00:57:53.410 --> 00:57:55.240
was five, four, three,
two, one call it.

00:57:55.240 --> 00:57:58.580
So there'd be nobody at level
one, nobody at level two,

00:57:58.580 --> 00:58:01.210
maybe two kids at level
3, most of the kids at

00:58:01.210 --> 00:58:03.180
level four and five.

00:58:03.180 --> 00:58:07.870
And six months with a laptop, it
got to like 30% of the kids

00:58:07.870 --> 00:58:09.470
were like in level two.

00:58:09.470 --> 00:58:12.080
And so that was pretty
compelling.

00:58:12.080 --> 00:58:20.090
But yeah, I think how OLPC has
reacted is sort of saying,

00:58:20.090 --> 00:58:26.690
it's hard to say this, the
teachers are a critical part

00:58:26.690 --> 00:58:28.520
of education.

00:58:28.520 --> 00:58:32.010
So what do you do when the
teachers don't show up, or are

00:58:32.010 --> 00:58:34.720
illiterate, or are scared
of the technology?

00:58:34.720 --> 00:58:38.700
Can you make the technology easy
enough to use so the kids

00:58:38.700 --> 00:58:41.300
can learn on their own
without the teachers?

00:58:41.300 --> 00:58:44.240
And that's the grand experiment
that OLPC is now

00:58:44.240 --> 00:58:46.920
doing with pretty rigorous
social scientists.

00:58:46.920 --> 00:58:50.590
I think they've got three
different sort of great

00:58:50.590 --> 00:58:56.230
thinkers on how we learn to
read and so forth in a

00:58:56.230 --> 00:58:58.125
non-reading society.

00:58:58.125 --> 00:59:03.950
I think there's been very little
significant research

00:59:03.950 --> 00:59:06.590
done on how a culture
with absolutely no

00:59:06.590 --> 00:59:07.625
reading goes to reading.

00:59:07.625 --> 00:59:12.360
So they're studying that to say,
how do we get around this

00:59:12.360 --> 00:59:16.360
problem of teachers
and schools?

00:59:16.360 --> 00:59:18.150
It's radical.

00:59:18.150 --> 00:59:20.170
It's only part of the program.

00:59:20.170 --> 00:59:23.200
A lot of the program is dealing
in the infrastructure,

00:59:23.200 --> 00:59:27.480
transforming a lot of schools
in Latin America.

00:59:27.480 --> 00:59:33.000
But then, the big problems, as
I think one of the lead execs

00:59:33.000 --> 00:59:36.540
at One Laptop per Child puts it,
the rich kids are the ones

00:59:36.540 --> 00:59:38.270
that get to go to school.

00:59:38.270 --> 00:59:40.350
There's 100, 200 million
kids that don't even

00:59:40.350 --> 00:59:41.520
get to go to school.

00:59:41.520 --> 00:59:43.630
How do you reach those kids?

00:59:43.630 --> 00:59:45.810
So that sort of takes the
politics out of it.

00:59:45.810 --> 00:59:48.500
They're not getting to go
to school, can we do

00:59:48.500 --> 00:59:49.340
something by them?

00:59:49.340 --> 00:59:55.350
Because their life opportunities
are extremely

00:59:55.350 --> 00:59:58.110
limited if they don't ever learn
how to read, if they

00:59:58.110 --> 00:59:59.150
don't get to go to school,
if they don't

00:59:59.150 --> 01:00:00.960
get access to education.

01:00:00.960 --> 01:00:02.880
VIVIAN CROMWELL: And they are
usually the group that's a

01:00:02.880 --> 01:00:05.670
little bit more hungry
for knowledge.

01:00:05.670 --> 01:00:08.420
MARY LOU JEPSEN: Yeah, hungry
for opportunity, and feel

01:00:08.420 --> 01:00:13.220
lucky, so they'll work
hard, when they can.

01:00:13.220 --> 01:00:19.980
So that's a long-winded answer
to the question.

01:00:19.980 --> 01:00:22.780
VIVIAN CROMWELL: I think
